      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis performed on at least two mesh densities; GCI < 5% on the QoI (RH index) at the worst-case operating point.",
      "rationale": "Three polyhedral meshes (4.2 M, 8.7 M, 17.1 M cells) were generated. GCI on RH at 2.0 L/min / 3500 RPM was 3.8%, satisfying the < 5% threshold. The 8.7 M cell mesh was selected for production runs as the optimal cost-accuracy trade-off."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, rotational speed, fluid temperature) documented with measurement uncertainty; conditions bracket the CPB operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation experiment used a mock circulatory loop with calibrated ultrasonic flow probes (±1.5%) and pressure transducers (±0.5 mmHg). Outlet pressure was set to 25–35 mmHg, consistent with CPB circuit resistance. Temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.5 °C. All five operating points fall within the documented test envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (NRMSE or equivalent) reported for the primary QoI; agreement within 15% across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "NRMSE of 8.3% on RH across five CPB operating points satisfies the 15% threshold. Worst-case point-wise error is 12.1% at 3.0 L/min / 2500 RPM. The supplementary HemoLab VAD cross-check (outlet pressure 100–120 mmHg) showed 11% agreement on converted RH values and is cited as corroborating evidence; however, the operating pressure regime of that dataset differs from the CPB COU by approximately 80 mmHg, a distinction not explicitly examined in the output comparison rationale."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (RH index) is directly linked to the clinical decision criterion (RH < 1); sensitivity of RH to the decision variable (impeller tip clearance) is demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "RH is the regulatory acceptance metric for hemolysis comparison against predicate devices. Parametric CFD runs over tip clearances of 0.10–0.25 mm demonstrate monotonic RH sensitivity, confirming the QoI is appropriate for identifying worst-case tolerance conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments conducted at conditions representative of CPB use (flow rate, pressure, pump geometry, fluid); differences between validation and COU conditions are identified and their impact on prediction confidence is assessed.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation experiment was conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at CPB-representative flow rates and outlet pressures. Fluid properties (bovine blood, haematocrit 33%) are accepted surrogates for human blood in hemolysis testing per ISO 10993-4. The supplementary HemoLab dataset is acknowledged as a cross-check from a different pressure regime; the assessment team noted strong geometric and flow-rate overlap and considered the dataset broadly applicable without performing a formal pressure-sensitivity analysis to quantify the impact of the 80 mmHg outlet pressure difference on the damage model exponent."
    },
